### Arc with Cubic Bézier (Four Control Points)

A more flexible curve with two control points.

```scheme
;; Cubic Bézier arc
(define (draw)
  (let* ((t (/ (mod (millis) 2800) 2800.0))
         (x0 60) (y0 300)
         (x1 120) (y1 100)
         (x2 280) (y2 100)
         (x3 340) (y3 300)
         (t1 (- 1 t))
         (x (+ (* t1 t1 t1 x0)
               (* 3 t1 t1 t x1)
               (* 3 t1 t t x2)
               (* t t t x3)))
         (y (+ (* t1 t1 t1 y0)
               (* 3 t1 t1 t y1)
               (* 3 t1 t t y2)
               (* t t t y3))))
    (motion/clear)
    ;; Draw control points
    (motion/circle x0 y0 5 \"stroke\")
    (motion/circle x1 y1 5 \"stroke\")
    (motion/circle x2 y2 5 \"stroke\")
    (motion/circle x3 y3 5 \"stroke\")
    ;; Draw the moving point
    (motion/circle x y 11 \"fill\")))

(draw)
```

[VISUAL: A smooth S-curve connecting four points, influenced by the two interior control points]

The cubic Bézier formula allows inflection points and asymmetric curves.

